4. Mitral regurgitation - papillary muscle or chordae abnormalities.

[!INFO] The HOCM murmur
#2020SBR-JUL/Q11
The murmur is a high-pitched, crescendo-decrescendo, mid-systolic murmur usually heard best at the left lower sternal border; it typically ends before the second heart sound. It ❗does not radiate to the carotids like that of aortic stenosis (AS), but may radiate to the base and apex of the heart.

[!INFO] "The HOCM murmur is louder when the ventricular volume is low, as the outflow tract is narrower".
The murmur and the gradient across the LVOT will ⬇⬇decrease⬇⬇ with

  • an increase in preload (Squatting) or
  • an increase in afterload (handgrip). Source

The gradient and the murmur will increase with

  • a decrease in preload (Valsalva maneuver, diuretics, standing). Certain maneuvers can affect murmurs auscultated in HOCM.

See ❗[[Basic Sciencies - MCQ reading#Dynamic auscultation|Dynamic auscultation]]

  • If asymptomatic, no medication neded.
    #2020SBR-JUL/Q11
  • MVP produces a mid systolic click with a late systolic murmur. It is the only significant late systolic murmur. Source
  • Increased preload AND increased afterload will (counterintuitively) decrease the MVP murmur.
    • Conversely, maneuvers that ⬇decrease left ventricular volume (e.g., Valsalva or standing) will cause the click and murmur of MVP to occur earlier in systole and become more prominent.Source (Counterintuitive.. yes)
    • Handgrip (i.e ⬆ afterload) will ⬇decrease the MVP murmurSource (also counterintuitive)

Causes of unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia

From Harrisons

  1. Haemolysis
  2. Ineffective erythropoiesis
  3. Defective conjugation - Criggler najjar and Gilbert
  4. Acquired conjugation defects
    1. It's possible in cirrhosis but usually, "conjugation is better preserved than other aspects of bilirubin metabolism like canalicular secretion".
    2. Gentamicin can inhibit UGT1A1 -> unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia
      Goal of treatment is to prevent recurrences and promote healing of existing lesions.

Crohn's disease

Induction of remission

  • steroids - oral or IV
    • In midly active Crohn's disease with low risk, oral budesonide is used because is has low systemic absorption.
    • IV steroids are used for severe disease. Source
  • Second line agent - anti TNF-alpha antibodies -> infliximab, adalimumab; best used in combination with azathioprine.
    • (can be used as steroid sparing agents)
    • They induce healing of lesions
    • Intermittent dosing leads to formation of inactivating antibodies -> regular dosing is required.
  • Azathioprine, mercaptopurine and MTX can also be used.
  • Exclusive enteral nutrition helps to induce remission.
  • aminosalicilates are of NO benefit.

Maintenance

Except for steroids, the others can be used for maintenance.

Ulcerative colitis

Induction of remission

  • Local 5 amino salicilates are the mainstay of treatment. (Mesalazine , Olsalazine, Balsazide, Sulfasalazine)
  • They act topically.
  • Delivered via enema (for left sided colitis) or suppository (proctitis) or oral for extensive disease.
  • Mechanism of action unknown.
  • Second line options for resistant disease: anti TNF-alpha inhibitors (infliximab, adalimumab) or anti integrin (vedolizumab), or tofacitinib(Oral inhibitor of JAK pathway).
  • Severe colitis - IV hydrocortisone with enoxaparin to prevent thromboembolism.

📑Alcoholic hepatitis

#2020SBR-JUL/Q28
Biochemical features

  • Incr. GGT
  • AST : ALT ratio > 2 (rarely seen in other hepatic diseases) (UpToDate)
  • However, ALT and ALT are usually less than 300, almost never exceed 500;
  • Jaundice - Direct / conjugated.[[2022-November#Classification of causes of hyperbilirubinaemia|Causes Of Hyperbilirubinaemia]]
  • Alcohol abuse is associated with macrocytosis (exact cause is unknown). MCV can even be used as a surrogate marker for degree of alcohol abuse.
  • Heavy / chronic alcohol abuse can cause megalobastic (causing macrocytosis) anaemai due to bone marrow toxicity of alcohol +/- folate deficiency.

Transaminases

#2020SBR-JUL/Q28

[!INFO] Some physiology
In liver lobules, the central zone 3 which is most vulnerable to ishemic injury due to the distance from the vascular supply also has the highest concentration of AST. Therefore, ischemic injury causes rise of AST befoer ALT. Source

Both AST and ALT enzymes require pyridoxal-5’-phosphate (vitamin B6) to function properly. Its absence in nutritionally-deficient heavy-drinkers has a much larger effect on the production of ALT than that of AST, causing the AST:ALT ratio to rise. A normal AST:ALT ratio should be <1.
$$
normally,
\Large {AST < ALT}
$$
In patients with alcoholic liver disease, the AST:ALT ratio is >1 in 92% of patients, and >2 in 70%.13

  • AST:ALT scores >2 are, therefore, strongly suggestive of alcoholic liver disease and
  • scores <1 more suggestive of NAFLD/NASH.Source

[!TIP] Mnemonic
aLcohol = Liver = Low ALT

liver transaminases in cholestatis

In the evaluation of cholestatis and elevated liver enzymes:

  • AST:ALT ratio < 1.5 (i.e ⬆⬆ALT) => Extrahepatic obstruction
  • AST:ALT ratio > 1.5 (i.e ⬆⬆AST) => Intrahepatic obstruction more likely

Causes of massive transaminitis

  1. Paracetamol overdose and toxicity
  2. Viral hepatitis
  3. hypoxic / ischemic liver injury
  4. [[Gastroenterology MCQ discussion#Q 13 Wilsons disease|Wilson's disease]]
